******
[3] Cholera, imported - Bahamas
Date: Fri 21 Oct 2011
Source: Bahamas Weekly [edited]
http://www.thebahamasweekly.com/publish/bis-news-updates/Ministry_of_Health_notice_on_Cholera18414.shtml


The Ministry of Health wishes to report that a person was intercepted
at sea and detained at the Detention Centre. The detainee appeared
unwell on arrival, was treated for suspected cholera, and has since
been repatriated. There was no contact between the person and the
community-at-large. Laboratory tests later confirmed cholera.

As reported, Haiti has an increased rate of cholera. The Ministry of
Health continues its heightened surveillance activities and other
necessary precautions to identify cases and prevent the transmission
of cholera in The Bahamas. The public is reminded to use clean water
and maintain good hygienic practices to prevent cholera from
spreading.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The origin of the cholera-infected individual is not stated, but
given the ongoing epidemic of the disease on the island of Hispanola,
particularly in Haiti, it is more than likely that the person was
infected there. Whether additional cases will occur in the area of the
detention center on Nassau will depend on the adequacy of the sewage
system there. - Mod.LL

The interactive HealthMap/ProMED map for the Bahamas is available at
